# Alipajand Personal Site – Cursor Rules

## Context
- **Project:** Ali Pajand personal website & blog.
- **Tech Stack:** Next.js App Router (v16), React 19, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS.
- **Purpose:** Portfolio, writing, and experiments around developer experience and AI tooling.

## Code & Architecture
- Use **TypeScript** for all application and test code.
- Prefer **functional React components**, server components by default; mark as client only when using hooks or browser-only APIs.
- Keep reusable UI in `components/` and colocate hooks under `components/**/hooks` or `utils/hooks`.
- Keep data-only modules (e.g. `data/*`, `utils/*`) free of React/DOM concerns.

## Testing
- Use **Jest + Testing Library** (`@testing-library/react`, `@testing-library/jest-dom`) for all UI and hook tests.
- Co-locate specs in `__tests__` folders that mirror the source path and filename.
- Test **behavior and contracts** (DOM, accessibility, props) rather than implementation details.

## Content
- Blog posts live in `content/posts` as Markdown with frontmatter (title, date, summary, tags, slug, published).
- Slugs should be **kebab-case** and stable once published.
- Avoid breaking existing URLs; when changing content, preserve slugs unless there is a compelling reason.

## AI Usage
- When using AI to edit code, preserve existing style, patterns, and public component APIs unless explicitly asked to refactor.
- Prefer small, focused changes with passing tests over large rewrites.
- Keep comments high-signal: explain intent, constraints, or trade-offs—not obvious behavior.